Basic Stream Problems
1. Sum all numbers in a list
int sum = numbers.stream()
                 .mapToInt(Integer::intValue)
                 .sum();

2. Find maximum number
int max = numbers.stream()
                 .max(Integer::compare)
                 .orElseThrow();


3. Count even numbers
long count = numbers.stream()
                 .filter(n -> n % 2 == 0)
                 .count();


4. Convert list of strings to uppercase
List<String> result = names.stream()
                 .map(String::toUpperCase)
                 .toList();


5. Remove duplicates
List<Integer> unique = numbers.stream()
                 .distinct()
                 .toList();


2️⃣ Filtering Problems
6. Find numbers greater than 10
List<Integer> result = numbers.stream()
                 .filter(n -> n > 10)
                 .toList();


7. Find first string starting with "A"
Optional<String> result = names.stream()
                 .filter(n -> n.startsWith("A"))
                 .findFirst();


8. Check if any number is negative
boolean exists = numbers.stream()
                 .anyMatch(n -> n < 0);


9. Check if all numbers are positive
boolean allPositive = numbers.stream()
                 .allMatch(n -> n > 0);


10. Find strings longer than 5 characters
List<String> result = names.stream()
                 .filter(n -> n.length() > 5)
                 .toList();


3️⃣ Transformation Problems
11. Convert list of objects to list of names
List<String> names = users.stream()
                 .map(User::getName)
                 .toList();


12. Square all numbers
List<Integer> result = numbers.stream()
                 .map(n -> n * n)
                 .toList();


13. Convert strings to their lengths
List<Integer> lengths = names.stream()
                 .map(String::length)
                 .toList();


14. Convert list to comma-separated string
String result = names.stream()
                 .collect(Collectors.joining(", "));


15. Create map from list
Map<Integer,String> map = users.stream()
                 .collect(Collectors.toMap(
                    User::getId,
                    User::getName
                 ));


4️⃣ Aggregation Problems
16. Calculate average value
double avg = numbers.stream()
                .mapToInt(Integer::intValue)
                .average()
                .orElse(0);


17. Count words in list
long count = words.stream().count();


18. Find longest string
String longest = names.stream()
                .max(Comparator.comparingInt(String::length))
                .orElse("");


19. Sum property of objects
int total = orders.stream()
          .mapToInt(Order::getAmount)
          .sum();


20. Find second highest number
int second = numbers.stream()
        .sorted(Comparator.reverseOrder())
        .skip(1)
        .findFirst()
        .orElseThrow();


5️⃣ Grouping Problems
These use Collectors.groupingBy().

21. Group employees by department
Map<String,List<Employee>> result = employees.stream()
                                        .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
                                        Employee::getDepartment
                                    ));


22. Count employees per department
Map<String,Long> result = employees.stream()
                            .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
                                Employee::getDepartment,
                                Collectors.counting()
                            ));


23. Group strings by length
Map<Integer,List<String>> result = names.stream()
                                    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
                                        String::length
                                    ));


24. Partition numbers into even/odd
Map<Boolean,List<Integer>> result = numbers.stream()
                                    .collect(Collectors.partitioningBy(
                                          n -> n % 2 == 0
                                    ));


25. Group orders by status
Map<OrderStatus,List<Order>> result = orders.stream()
                                    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
                                        Order::getStatus
                                    ));


6️⃣ Advanced Stream Problems

26. Flatten list of lists
List<Integer> result = lists.stream()
                        .flatMap(List::stream)
                        .toList();


27. Find duplicate elements
Set<Integer> duplicates = numbers.stream()
                            .filter(n ->
                                Collections.frequency(numbers, n) > 1)
                            .collect(Collectors.toSet());


28. Get top 3 highest numbers
List<Integer> top3 = numbers.stream()
                        .sorted(Comparator.reverseOrder())
                        .limit(3)
                        .toList();


29. Convert list to frequency map
Map<String,Long> freq = words.stream()
                        .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
                             w -> w,
                             Collectors.counting()
                        ));


30. Get unique characters from string
Set<Character> chars = input.chars()
                        .mapToObj(c -> (char)c)
                        .collect(Collectors.toSet());

31. Find the top 5 most frequent words in a list.
List<String> result = words.stream()
                .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
                    w -> w, Collectors.counting())
                    )
                .entrySet()
                .stream()
                .sorted(Map.Entry.<String,Long>
                     comparingByValue().reversed())
                .limit(5)
                .map(Map.Entry::getKey)
                .toList();

Pipeline:
words
 → group
 → count
 → sort
 → top 5

32. Find the first non-repeating character in a string.
Expected solution:
char result = str.chars()
                .mapToObj(c -> (char)c)
                .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
                    c -> c,
                    LinkedHashMap::new,
                    Collectors.counting()
                ))
                .entrySet()
                .stream()
                .filter(e -> e.getValue() == 1)
                .map(Map.Entry::getKey)
                .findFirst()
                .orElseThrow();

33. Find duplicate elements in a list.
34. Find top N frequent elements.
35. Flatten deeply nested collections.
    Example:
    List<List<List<Integer>>>
36. Detect inefficient stream usage in code review.
    Example:
    list.stream()
        .filter(...)
        .collect(Collectors.toList())
        .stream()
        .map(...)

    Correct answer:
    Combine pipelines.

Streams Code/Debugging Scenarios:
1. What's the output of:
Stream<Integer> stream = List.of(1,2,3).stream();
stream.forEach(System.out::println);
stream.count();

Result: IllegalStateException: stream has already been operated upon

Why: Streams are single-use pipelines. Once a terminal operation runs, the stream is consumed.

Fix: Create a new stream.
List<Integer> list = List.of(1,2,3);
list.stream().forEach(System.out::println);
list.stream().count();

2. Code
   list.stream()
       .filter(x -> {
           System.out.println("Filtering");
           return x > 5;
       });

   Output: Nothing prints.
   Why: No terminal operation exists. Streams are lazy.
   Fix: Add terminal operation.
   list.stream()
       .filter(x -> x > 5)
       .toList();

3. Code
   Stream.iterate(1, n -> n + 1)
         .filter(n -> n < 0)
         .findFirst();

   Result: Program never finishes.
   Why: infinite stream, filter condition never satisfied.
   Fix: Add limit.
   Stream.iterate(1, n -> n + 1)
         .limit(100)
         .filter(n -> n < 0)
         .findFirst();

4. Code
List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();
IntStream.range(1,1000)
         .parallel()
         .forEach(result::add);

    Problem: Results may be corrupted or missing.
    Why: ArrayList is not thread-safe.
    Fix: Use collector.
    List<Integer> result = IntStream.range(1,1000)
                        .parallel()
                        .boxed()
                        .toList();

5. Code
   int sum = 0;
   numbers.stream().forEach(n -> sum += n);

   Problem: Won't compile (effectively final variable). Even if workaround is used → unsafe in parallel streams.
   Fix: Use reduce.
   int sum = numbers.stream().reduce(0, Integer::sum);

6. Code
   class User {
      int id;
   }
   users.stream().distinct().toList();

   Problem: Duplicates remain.
   Why: distinct() relies on: equals() hashCode()
   Fix: Override both methods.

7. Code
   stream.peek(x -> saveToDatabase(x))
         .toList();

   Problem: Side effects hidden inside pipeline.
   Why: peek() is intended only for debugging.
   Fix: Separate side effects.

8. Code
   numbers.parallelStream()
       .filter(n -> n > 10)
       .findFirst();

   Problem: Parallelism becomes inefficient.
   Why: findFirst() preserves ordering.
   Fix: Use findAny()

9. Code
    list.parallelStream()
      .forEach(System.out::println);

   Output: Order may change.
   Example:
    5
    1
    3
    2
    4
   Why: Parallel streams do not guarantee order.
   Fix: forEachOrdered()

10. Code
    list.stream().forEach(list::remove);

    Result: ConcurrentModificationException

    Why: You modify collection while iterating.
    Fix: Use filter. list.removeIf(x -> condition);


Debugging Trick
When debugging streams, add logging with peek.
Example:
stream
 .peek(x -> System.out.println("Input: " + x))
 .filter(x -> x > 5)
 .peek(x -> System.out.println("Filtered: " + x))
 .map(x -> x * 2)
 .toList();

But remove this after debugging.

11. Code
    Stream.of(1,2,3)
          .filter(x -> {
              System.out.println("filter " + x);
              return x > 1;
          });

    Question: What prints?
    Answer: Nothing

    Why: Streams are lazy. Without a terminal operation, nothing runs.

12. Code
    Stream.of(1,2,3,4)
          .filter(x -> {
              System.out.println("filter " + x);
              return x % 2 == 0;
          })
          .findFirst();

    Output:
    filter 1
    filter 2

    Why: findFirst() stops the pipeline once the first match appears.

13. Code
    Stream.of(1,2,3,4)
          .map(x -> {
              System.out.println("map " + x);
              return x * 2;
          })
          .filter(x -> {
              System.out.println("filter " + x);
              return x > 4;
          })
          .findFirst();

    Output:
    map 1
    filter 2
    map 2
    filter 4
    map 3
    filter 6

    Why: Streams operate element-by-element, not stage-by-stage. Pipeline actually behaves like: map → filter → next element

14. Code
    Stream.iterate(1, n -> n + 1)
          .filter(n -> n < 0)
          .findFirst();

    Result: Program never finishes.
    Why: Infinite stream + condition never satisfied.

15. Code
    Stream<Integer> s = Stream.of(1,2,3);
    s.count();
    s.forEach(System.out::println);

    Result: IllegalStateException
    Why: Streams are single-use pipelines.

16. Code
    List<Integer> list = List.of(1,2,3,4,5);
    list.parallelStream()
        .forEach(System.out::print);

    Possible Output: 35142
    Why: Parallel streams do not preserve order.
    Use: forEachOrdered()


17. Code
    List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>(List.of(1,2,3));
    list.stream().forEach(list::remove);

    Result: ConcurrentModificationException
    Why: You cannot modify a collection while streaming it.

18. Puzzle: distinct() Surprise
    Code
    class User {
       int id;
    }

    List<User> users = List.of(
        new User(1),
        new User(1)
    );

    users.stream()
         .distinct()
         .count();

    Output: 2

    Why: distinct() relies on: equals() hashCode()

19: Puzzle: limit() Efficiency
    Code
    Stream.of(1,2,3,4,5)
          .filter(x -> {
              System.out.println("filter " + x);
              return x > 2;
          })
          .limit(1)
          .toList();

    Output: filter 1
    filter 2
    filter 3

    Why: limit() stops pipeline once enough elements pass.

20. Puzzle: peek() Trap
    Code: Stream.of(1,2,3).peek(System.out::println);

    Output: Nothing
    Why: Again: no terminal operation. peek() is intermediate.

Almost every Stream puzzle relies on four rules:
1️⃣ Streams are lazy
2️⃣ Operations run element-by-element
3️⃣ Streams are single-use
4️⃣ Parallel streams break ordering
If you remember those, most Streams puzzles become easy.

1️⃣ Sorting Before Limiting
Code
list.stream()
    .sorted()
    .limit(10)
    .toList();

What you may think: Only the first 10 elements are sorted.
Reality: The entire list is sorted first.
Why: sorted() must examine all elements.
Better approach: Use a priority queue if the dataset is huge.

2️⃣ Parallel Stream Slower Than Sequential
Code
list.parallelStream()
    .map(x -> x * 2)
    .toList();

Assumption: Parallel = faster.
Reality: Often slower.
Why: Parallel overhead includes:
            thread scheduling
            splitting
            merging results
Rule
Parallel streams help only when:
large dataset + CPU-heavy computation


3️⃣ Boxing Overhead
Code
list.stream()
    .map(x -> x * 2)
    .reduce(0, Integer::sum);

Problem: Boxing/unboxing overhead.
Better: list.stream()
    .mapToInt(x -> x * 2)
    .sum();

Primitive streams are faster.

4️⃣ distinct() on Large Data
Code
list.stream()
    .distinct()
    .toList();

Problem: distinct() internally uses HashSet.
Impact: Huge memory overhead for millions of elements.

5️⃣ Nested Streams (O(n²))
Code
users.stream()
     .forEach(u ->
         orders.stream()
               .filter(o -> o.userId()==u.id())
     );

Complexity: O(n²)

Better approach: Index orders first:
Map<Integer,List<Order>> map =
orders.stream()
      .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Order::userId));


6️⃣ Expensive filter() Order
Code
stream
.filter(x -> expensiveCheck(x))
.filter(x -> x > 10)

Problem: Expensive check runs unnecessarily.
Better: stream
            .filter(x -> x > 10)
            .filter(this::expensiveCheck)

Put cheap filters first.

7️⃣ Collecting Huge Streams
Code
List<Data> data =
stream.collect(Collectors.toList());

Problem: Memory explosion if dataset is huge.
Better: Process elements incrementally.
Example: stream.forEach(this::writeToFile);


8️⃣ Parallel Stream with Blocking IO
Code
users.parallelStream()
     .forEach(user -> httpCall(user));

Problem: Threads block.
Parallel streams use: ForkJoinPool.commonPool. Blocking tasks can freeze the application.
Better: Use custom thread pool.

9️⃣ Multiple Stream Pipelines
Code
list.stream()
    .filter(x -> x > 10)
    .toList()
    .stream()
    .map(x -> x * 2)

Problem: Two pipelines → extra iteration.
Better: list.stream()
    .filter(x -> x > 10)
    .map(x -> x * 2)


🔟 findFirst() Killing Parallel Performance
Code
stream.parallel()
      .filter(x -> x > 10)
      .findFirst();

Problem: Ordering must be preserved.
Result: Parallelism reduced.
Better: findAny()

Stream API Suggestions:
Rule 1 - Prefer primitive streams. IntStream / LongStream
Rule 2 - Avoid parallel streams for IO tasks.
Rule 3 - Avoid multiple stream pipelines.
Rule 4 - Place cheap filters first.
Rule 5 - Avoid collecting huge streams into memory.

1️⃣ Find the First Non-Repeating Word in a Sentence
Problem: Given a sentence, return the first word that appears only once.
Example: "java streams are powerful and streams are fast"

Expected result: powerful

Stream Solution
String result = Arrays.stream(sentence.split(" "))
      .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
          w -> w,
          LinkedHashMap::new,
          Collectors.counting()))
      .entrySet()
      .stream()
      .filter(e -> e.getValue() == 1)
      .map(Map.Entry::getKey)
      .findFirst()
      .orElse(null);

Why tricky: requires LinkedHashMap to preserve order.

2️⃣ Find Missing Numbers in a Sequence
Problem: Given numbers from 1..N, find missing ones.
Example: input: [1,2,4,6] N=6
Output: [3,5]

Stream Solution
List<Integer> missing = IntStream.rangeClosed(1,6)
         .filter(n -> !list.contains(n))
         .boxed()
         .toList();

Why tricky: contains() makes complexity O(n²). Interviewers often expect optimization.

3️⃣ Convert List of Strings into a Frequency Map (Case-Insensitive)
Example: ["Java","java","Python","JAVA"]

Output: {java=3, python=1}

Solution
Map<String,Long> map = words.stream()
     .map(String::toLowerCase)
     .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
         w -> w,
         Collectors.counting()
     ));


4️⃣ Find the Most Frequent Element
Example: [1,2,3,2,4,2,5]

Expected: 2

Solution
int result = numbers.stream()
       .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
           n -> n,
           Collectors.counting()))
       .entrySet()
       .stream()
       .max(Map.Entry.comparingByValue())
       .get()
       .getKey();


5️⃣ Group Strings by Anagram
Example: ["eat","tea","tan","ate","nat","bat"]

Output:
{
  aet=[eat,tea,ate],
  ant=[tan,nat],
  abt=[bat]
}

Solution
Map<String,List<String>> result = words.stream()
     .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(w -> {
         char[] arr = w.toCharArray();
         Arrays.sort(arr);
         return new String(arr);
     }));

Why tricky: requires transformation key.

6️⃣ Flatten Deeply Nested Collections
Example: List<List<List<Integer>>>
Goal → flat list.
Solution:
List<Integer> result = nested.stream()
      .flatMap(List::stream)
      .flatMap(List::stream)
      .toList();

Why tricky: requires understanding nested flattening.

7️⃣ Find Longest Word in Each Sentence
Input: ["Java streams are powerful", "Streams simplify data processing"]

Output: [powerful, processing]

Solution
List<String> result = sentences.stream()
         .map(s -> Arrays.stream(s.split(" "))
              .max(Comparator.comparingInt(String::length))
              .orElse(""))
         .toList();


8️⃣ Partition Numbers into Prime and Non-Prime
Solution:
Map<Boolean,List<Integer>> result = numbers.stream()
       .collect(Collectors.partitioningBy(n ->
           IntStream.range(2,n)
                    .noneMatch(i -> n % i == 0)
       ));

Why tricky: embedded stream inside predicate.

9️⃣ Merge Two Lists Without Duplicates
Example: [1,2,3] + [3,4,5]

Output: [1,2,3,4,5]

Solution
List<Integer> result = Stream.concat(list1.stream(), list2.stream())
      .distinct()
      .toList();


🔟 Find Top 3 Highest Salaries per Department
Input: Employee(dept, salary)

Solution
Map<String,List<Employee>> result = employees.stream()
         .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
             Employee::getDept,
             Collectors.collectingAndThen(
                 Collectors.toList(),
                 list -> list.stream()
                     .sorted(Comparator.comparing(Employee::getSalary)
                     .reversed())
                     .limit(3)
                     .toList()
             )
         ));

Why tricky: requires collectingAndThen.

1️⃣ Top K Frequent Words
Problem: Return the top K most frequent words.
Example ["java","python","java","go","java","python"]
k = 2
Output [java, python]

Stream Idea
List<String> result = words.stream()
     .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
         w -> w,
         Collectors.counting()))
     .entrySet()
     .stream()
     .sorted(Map.Entry.<String,Long>comparingByValue().reversed())
     .limit(k)
     .map(Map.Entry::getKey)
     .toList();


2️⃣ Find Duplicate Words With Counts
Problem: Return only words that appear more than once.
Stream Idea
Map<String,Long> duplicates = words.stream()
     .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
         w -> w,
         Collectors.counting()))
     .entrySet()
     .stream()
     .filter(e -> e.getValue() > 1)
     .collect(Collectors.toMap(
         Map.Entry::getKey,
         Map.Entry::getValue));


3️⃣ Group Employees by Department and Highest Salary
Problem: Return the highest paid employee per department.
Map<String, Optional<Employee>> result = employees.stream()
         .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
             Employee::getDepartment,
             Collectors.maxBy(
                 Comparator.comparing(Employee::getSalary)
             )
         ));


4️⃣ Find Second Highest Salary Per Department
Map<String, Employee> result = employees.stream()
         .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
             Employee::getDepartment,
             Collectors.collectingAndThen(
                 Collectors.toList(),
                 list -> list.stream()
                     .sorted(Comparator.comparing(Employee::getSalary)
                     .reversed())
                     .skip(1)
                     .findFirst()
                     .orElse(null)
             )
         ));


